I chose to rename the a multitude of functions for legibility and convienance sake. I renamed yr to year to complete the word as it is very short without the breevation and can prevent confusion. The same resonsing was behind my decision to rename mnth to month. the name weathersit did not make sense so i renamed the column to weathercd to abrreviate weather code as the variable indicated the weather. I renamed temp to actual_temp, atemp to real_feel, hum to humidity, casual to casual_users, registered to registered_users and cnt to total_cnt to more accurately reflect what each columns aimed to measure. All of these renames make the data frame more understandable and userfriendly.

bike_data <- bike_data %>%

mutate(season = factor(season, levels = c( "Spring", "Summer","Fall", "Winter")))

In this example, I first label the different factors and first turn season into a factor style column by directly altering bike_data data frame using the mutate function. Then, I re-level specific labels in the required order by specifying them in that order after using labels in the factor function.

Question 2b

bike_data <- bike_data %>% 
mutate(workingday = factor(workingday, labels = c("no","yes"))) %>%
mutate(holiday = factor(holiday, labels = c("no","yes")))

In this example, we directly alter (factor) the bike_data data frame to turn numbers into corresponding words. I first specify that bike data data frame will be altered by using an assignment operator <- and referencing bike_data so that following function knows where to gather the input material, using a pipe to pass this to the mutate function. The mutate function allows the factor function to alter workingday, specifying the necesary labels using the labels function. I do the same process for Holiday. Note their is no need to re-level because they are in alphabetical order.

In this problem, I directly alter the bike_data data frame using the mutate function. I first specify that I want to turn the year column into a factor style and then specify the labels using the labels specifier within the factor function.

Question 2d

bike_data <- bike_data %>%

Again, I directly alter the bike_data dataframe using the mutate function and factor function to (1) change the columnn type of weathercd to a factor style and (2) specify the labels of each number using the label specifier within the factor function. bike_data <- bike_data %>%

bike_data %>%

facet_wrap(~season)+
labs(title = "2012 Bike Rentals in DC by Season ", x = "Month", y = "Bike rentals", subtitle = "Warmer seasons are associated with more bike rentals")

First, I factor month column in the bike_data dataframe by referencing the dataframe, including a pipe, and using the mutate and factor functions together to show the name of the month rather than a number for convienance. After, I start a new code chunk, refrencing the bike_data frame, a pipe, ggplot, where I specify the x and y axis using using the aes function, geom_col to indicate a bar chart, and facet wrap to create a panel of charts. Lastly, I used labs to specify the axis labels, title, and subtitle, using a + wherever necessary. It seems that fall is the busiest time of year.

Question 12

#Turn the Columns into Factors
car_data <- car_data %>% 
mutate(met_color = factor(met_color, labels = c("None","Metallic")))

car_data <- car_data %>% 
mutate(automatic = factor(automatic, labels = c("None","Automatic")))

car_data <- car_data %>% 
mutate(fuel_type = factor(fuel_type))

#Creating the Dummy Variables
car_data <- car_data %>%
  recipe(~.) %>%
  step_dummy(met_color, automatic, fuel_type, preserve = TRUE, one_hot = TRUE) %>%
  prep(training = car_data) %>%
  bake(new_data = car_data)
view(car_data)

This question asks us to create dummy variables based on 3 variables, met_color, Automatic, fuel_type. Before creating the dummy variables for each of the 3 variable, converted the column style to factor using a factor function within a mutate function so that the orginal data set is altered. Afterwards, I refrence car_data and include a pipe, use the recipe function, the step dummy function, the prep function, and the bake function, using pipes where neccesary. After doing this process for each variable, I use a view function to ensure the results are correct.
